node.text:
Shot-calling is something every basic carbine/pistol class should cover. It is essential for self-diagnosis in improving marksmanship, recoil control, and shooting speed. I don’t think certain skills make someone “advanced” or “level 2” but if there was one thing that elevates some shooters above others, it’s shot-calling. Make sure you shoot a target far enough away so you can’t see the impact before you walk up. This is why I like to go back 25m+, make my call, then walk up and paste hits.
-
This is a segment from my 3 hour carbine class that is available for free at TREX-ARMS.COM.
-

Dropping in the next few days is a 3+ hour video of my basic carbine class we filmed a couple months ago that contains some of the POIs and drills that I run students through. This will be a free video available at @trexarms. No pay wall. No subscription needed. Accessible at any time. If you need to check something before going to the range, or just want to listen to another shooter’s perspective on shooting. And yes… I demo quite a bit.
-
The next one will most likely be pistol or maybe movement/distance with carbine. We didn’t do anything too crazy in this class. It’s just some basics.

node.text: If you want to get better at anything, you first have to acknowledge you suck. You then need to look for WHERE you suck. I do some weird stuff in static positions and have been working on fixing that. This video clearly shows some of my deficiencies. One of which is how slow I’m getting on the gun arriving into position (mainly because I was focusing on my weight distribution and NOT standing back up). Everyone sucks at shooting. Some people just suck less than others. But there’s always room for improvement.

node.text:
Dudes on the internet say all the time that shooting skills aren’t enough to be a prepared 2A citizen. And you know what; they’re right. There’s a lot more skills to work on than just shooting to be an asset. And that’s exactly what we will be focusing more on in the future. This was a rather simple exercise conducted by the majority of our customer service team, marketing, and the owners of @trexarms. The next will dive into the problems we experienced during this particular evening and the one following that will focus on the problems from the previous. That’s how you grow as a team.
-

node.text:
Training on the range will NEVER be 1:1 realistic. Just like how 64 hour FF courses, live burn training, and fire academies don’t come close to the real thing either. You can introduce certain principles, train on your gear, and get more comfortable in that type of environment: but it’s an unreasonable and unrealistic expectation that flat range training can/should mimic gunfights 1:1. It can’t. Force-on-force can’t either, although it is better. This is why 95% of my flat range firearms training is strictly shooting. The other 5% is something weird like this drill; introducing some “looking” for targets, unconventional gear use, attention to detail, and some medical. But at the end of the day, the shooting in this drill is the same as the shooting in all my other drills… it’s shooting.
-

This is my favorite Glock setup for crushing at the range: Glock 17 with Trijicon SRO. I’m using my Silicone-carbide infused grip (fancy grip tape) Zev did for me years ago. It’s kinda nice.

node.text:
People naturally desire role models. They desire a group to be associated with, a tribe to be their identity. And there’s nothing wrong with that, God didn’t make us to be alone. But one of the most fascinating things is that in the process of seeking a tribe or role-model… people often opt for the average. The average business. The average gamer. The average political leader. The average shooter. The average military organization. Why? I honestly believe it’s because people prefer a goal that’s easier to attain. Within reach. Versus setting their sights high which is going to require working very hard. Why are the examples in this image the examples I’m using? Because they’re at the top from working really freaking hard. GOOD. So can you. But only if you set your sights high and get to work. If you’re going to look for role models to motivate yourself, look for role models that are going to push you out of your comfort zone. Role models that FAR exceed your current ability and capability. In shooting, business, leadership, gaming, and life.
-
Go straight to the top. Aim for the head.
-
#leadership #business #gaming #shooting

node.text:
The Holosun vs everyone debate is a pretty interesting one. Particularly with how volatile fans/users are on both sides. Here are some of my observations:
1. Holosun makes some good products. They also make some crappy ones.
2. Big-name companies like Trijicon make some good products and ALSO make some crappy ones.
3. Because of the manufacturing situation in China, Holosun products will always be cheaper than optics produced in the USA or in Europe.
4. Just because something is made in China doesn’t mean it will be inherently bad quality.
5. Just because a product is cheaper than a big-name product does not automatically make it better.
6. Making claims such as “Holosun is used and shot with more than Trijicon” makes Holosun-users look foolish (as it is simply not true) Likewise, claims from Aimpoint/Trijicon fan-boys that all Holosun products are trash, doesn’t make them look good either.
7. Making the claim that you can save money by buying a Holosun to then invest in training/ammo only works if you ACTUALLY go out and buy ammo and training.
8. Some people prefer to spend money with American companies that employ Americans.
9. While we cannot avoid all product-use/purchases from China, it is possible to limit many of your purchases that directly fund the CCP; An enemy of our values.
10. Breaking-in your product or coming to the conclusion your product is “good to go” should require much more than a couple range sessions or the word of your favorite “influencer”. Products generally work great when they aren’t used. Actually use your gear before making claims on the internet about how good it is.
11. Buy what makes you happy and what you can afford. Back up your claims. Don’t suck.
12. Part of affording equipment requires budgeting expenses. If you waste money on a bunch of crap that means you can’t afford an Aimpoint PRO and use that as justification to own a Sightmark, NCstar, or Holosun: that shows your priorities regarding gear.
13. Trijicon RMRs have this verse: “And so we have the prophetic word made more sure, to which you do well to pay attention as to a lamp shining in a dark place, until the day dawns and the morning star arises in your hearts.”

node.text:
Shot-calling is something every basic carbine/pistol class should cover. It is essential for self-diagnosis in improving marksmanship, recoil control, and shooting speed. I don’t think certain skills make someone “advanced” or “level 2” but if there was one thing that elevates some shooters above others, it’s shot-calling. Make sure you shoot a target far enough away so you can’t see the impact before you walk up. This is why I like to go back 25m+, make my call, then walk up and paste hits.
-
This is a segment from my 3 hour carbine class that is available for free at TREX-ARMS.COM.
